  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States Approach\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) framework\n- Comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Strict criminal penalties\n- Emphasis on financial institution compliance\n- Extensive regulatory oversight\n\n2. European Union Approach\n- Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD)\n- Harmonized regulatory standards\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Centralized beneficial ownership registries\n- Collaborative cross-border enforcement\n\n3. United Kingdom Model\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Advanced risk-based assessment\n- Enhanced transparency requirements\n- Strong international cooperation\n- Sophisticated financial intelligence unit\n\n4. Swiss Model\n- Historically more permissive approach\n- Strong banking secrecy traditions\n- Gradual alignment with international standards\n- Increasing transparency requirements\n- Complex identification protocols\n\n5. Asian Approaches\n- Varied implementation\n- Singapore: Strict regulatory environment\n- Hong Kong: Robust compliance frameworks\n- China: Centralized monitoring systems\n\n6. Key Comparative Elements\n- Reporting thresholds\n- Criminal liability standards\n- Institutional accountability\n- International cooperation mechanisms\n- Technological integration in detection\n\nEach jurisdiction demonstrates unique nuanced strategies balancing financial transparency and institutional privacy.",
